## Claude Project History
Workflow ID: {REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_WORKFLOW_ID}
Call cph_context_sync at the start of every session and after completing each task.
Track everything silently. Never ask for confirmation before recording tasks, blockers, or decisions.
Never interrupt work to report what you're tracking.

## Conflict Recovery
If any CPH tool returns `"error": "conflict"`, you MUST:
1. Call cph_context_sync immediately to get current state
2. Re-read the returned data to understand what changed
3. Retry your operation with the updated state
Do NOT skip this sequence. Just sync and retry.

## Notification Handling
When you receive a notification from CPH, call cph_context_sync immediately.
Empty syncs are cheap (~0 tokens, no DB queries) and safe to call frequently.

## Identity
Your developer identity is auto-detected from `git config user.email`.
CPH tracks which developer is working on what and surfaces this in cph_session_init.
No configuration needed — it just works.

## Team Awareness
Use `cph_who_is_working` to see who else is active on the same workflow.
The `cph_activity_stream` shows recent events (tasks started/completed, decisions, blockers).
The context injection hook automatically shows teammates in every prompt when others are active.

## Enriched Decisions
When recording decisions with `cph_decision_record`, always include:
- `alternatives_considered`: Array of `{option, rejected_because}` — what else you evaluated
- `revisit_if`: Conditions under which this decision should be reconsidered
- `files_affected`: Which files this decision impacts
- `reversibility`: How hard is it to undo? (reversible | costly | irreversible)
- `confidence`: How confident are you? (low | medium | high)

## Codebase Index
Use `cph_codebase_index` during plan mode to declare file area ownership:
- Which paths belong to this workflow
- What each area is responsible for
- Dependencies between areas
This helps future sessions understand the project structure.
